PRE-MARKET JAPANESE AND SOUTH KOREAN STOCK NEWS: Japan is said to ease part of export controls with South Korea
content:
JAPAN

Daiichi Sankyo (4568 JT) - Co. ENHERTU breast cancer treatment received US FDA approval. (Newswires)

Eisai (4523 JT) - Co.’s DAYVIGO gets approval from US FDA. (Newswires)

Japan Display (6740 JT) - Co. received a 3-month extension from banks regarding commitment lines of JPY 107bln. (Newswires)

Kansai Electric Power (9503 JT) - Co. is reportedly to halt its Takahama nuclear reactors, while the Co. commented and said it was not the source of the reports. (Newswires)

Mazda Motor (7261 JT) - Co. is planning to move some of its production from Thailand to Japan due to adverse impact of strong THB. (Newswires)

SoftBank (9984 JT) - US DoJ and FCC criticized a lawsuit by state attorney generals seeking to block the merger between SoftBank’s unit Sprint (S) and T-Mobile (TMUS). (WSJ)

Unizo (3258 JT) - Co. received offer from Lone Star. (Newswires)

Buybacks - Analysts anticipate Japanese companies to continue with their record share repurchases which have increased on every year but 1 since 2012. (Newswires)

Trade - Japan is said to ease part of export controls with South Korea according to press reports, while it was separately reported that South Korea, Japan and China agreed to accelerate trilateral FTA discussions. (Newswires/Yonhap)

Other News - Japan Cabinet Office Monthly Economic Report cut the overall economic assessment in which it stated that the domestic economy is recovering at a moderate pace and that weakness mainly among manufacturers is increasing further, while it added that exports have continued on a weak tone. (Newswires)

 

SOUTH KOREA

Hyundai Heavy Industries (009540 KS) - Co. receives KRW 438bln order for 2 LNG carriers. (Newswires)

Hyundai Mipo Dockyard (010620 KS) - Co. signs KRW 148.2bln contract for gas carriers. (Newswires)

SK Innovation (096770 KS) - Co. received contract to supply 500k electric vehicle batteries to Hyundai Motor (005380 KS) and Kia Motors (000270 KS). (Newswires)

DAILY ASIA-PAC OPENING NEWS
content:
ASIA-PAC

US President Trump said he had a very good talk with Chinese President Xi concerning “our giant Trade Deal” and that China has already started large scale purchases of agricultural products & more with a formal signing being arranged, while Chinese press confirmed the leaders had a discussion which was at the request of US President Trump. (Twitter/Global Times)

Chinese President Xi reportedly told US President Trump that US interference is harming Chinese interests, while other reports noted that President Xi is willing to continue meeting with US President Trump. (Xinhua/China Daily)

US Commerce Secretary Ross said the US has been very careful on providing exclusions to the Huawei entity list and reiterated the US could increase tariffs on China if they do not hold up to the trade deal. (Newswires)

Japan was said to ease part of export controls with South Korea, according to press reports. (Newswires)

 

UK/EU

House of Commons approved the second reading of PM Johnson's Brexit deal legislation as expected through a 358 v 234 vote or 124-vote majority vs. the Conservatives 80-seat majority. In related news, UK PM Johnson commented that there will be no alignment with the EU in the future relationship. (Newswires)

UK Chancellor Javid confirmed Andrew Bailey as the next Governor of the Bank of England to succeed Mark Carney who will remain as Governor until March 15th. (Newswires)

BoE’s Haskel (Dovish, Dissenter) said current data justifies looser monetary policy and that cutting interest rates now would be insurance against rates getting stuck near zero in the near future, while Haskel added the effects of unconventional policies such as QE are much more uncertain. (Newswires)

  • UK GDP (Q3) Q/Q 0.4% vs. Exp. 0.3% (Prev. 0.3%)
  • UK GDP (Q3) Y/Y 1.1% vs. Exp. 1.0% (Prev. 1.0%)
  • EU Consumer Confidence Flash (Dec) -8.1 vs. Exp. -7.0 (Prev. -7.2)

 

COMMODITIES

Baker Hughes Rig Count (20th Dec): Oil +18 at 685, Natgas -4 at 125, Total +14 at 813. (Newswires)

Saudi Arabia and Kuwait reportedly could agree to renew oil output in the shared neutral zone along the border between the countries by year-end. (Newswires)

French CGT workers voted to halt output at Petroineos Lavera refinery which has a capacity of 210k bpd, according to a union official. (Newswires) 

 

GEOPOLITICS

Syrian anti-aircraft defence fired at hostile missiles which allegedly came from Israel. (Newswires)

Center for Strategic and International Studies’ Victor Cha said possible launch sites in North Korea look that they are basically ready to go. (Twitter)

 

US

  • US GDP Final (Q3) 2.1% vs. Exp. 2.1% (Prev. 2.1%)
  • US Core PCE Prices Final (Q3) 2.1% vs. Exp. 2.1% (Prev. 2.1%)
  • US Core PCE Price Index (Nov) M/M 0.1% vs. Exp. 0.1% (Prev. 0.1%)
  • US Core PCE Price Index (Nov) Y/Y 1.6% vs. Exp. 1.6% (Prev. 1.6%, Rev. 1.7%)
  • US Personal Income (Nov) M/M 0.5% vs. Exp. 0.3% (Rev. 0.1%)
  • US Consumption (Nov) M/M 0.4% vs. Exp. 0.4% (Prev. 0.3%)

 

MARKET RECAP

There were fresh record highs for US stocks (seventh straight session); progress on US/China trade, and decent data were said to be the driving forces including unrevised Q3 GDP print, with the data also revealing consumer spending better than expected. Nike (NKE) were weighed on to end the week despite beating on top and bottom lines however margins fell short of expectations. Its Jordan brand hit over USD 1bln for the first time. The co.’s CEO said he has never been more optimistic on the future, although its CFO warned that he expects group gross profit margins to be flat YY in Q3, in-part due to trade tariffs. Despite the strong headline, NKE shares fell 2% with analysts highlighting the strong run NKE had this year, where shares hit a record high yesterday, therefore some might have been profit taking as we head towards the year end. Carmax (KMX) were hit after earnings which saw EPS miss by USD 0.18. Carnival (CCL) rallied after strong headline beats and guidance, which in sympathy boosted Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings (NCLH). The Health Care sector was one of the top performers on the last trading day of the week, driven by a slew of regulatory approvals. Merck (MRK) traded higher as it received FDA approval for its Ebola vaccine, Ervebo, for individuals 18 and over. Elsewhere, it received approval in Japan for its Keytruda for three new first line indications across advances renal cell carcinoma and recurrent or distant metastatic head and neck cancer. Gilead (GILD) traded positive after it announced it received approval for its treatment of chronic hepatitis C, Vosevi, in China from the China National Medical Products Administration. SPX +0.5% at 3221.20, NDX +0.4% at 8678.49, Dow +0.3% at 28455.29.

The bias was slightly towards bear-flattening, although yields were up by around 1bps or so. Traders attributed the unrevised Q3 GDP print, with the data also revealing consumer spending better than expected, and businesses spending on non-residential structures, like power infrastructure, wires noted. The small upward revision in Michigan sentiment was also said to be a contributing factor. The theme this week has been steepening of 2s10s, although that wasn't seen on Friday, with many desks wrapping up for the year, there was a quiet feel to Treasury trade, which may again be seen in the early part of next week, before the Christmas holidays. US T-note futures (H0) settled 2 ticks lower at 128-08.
